Wyverns (sometimes referred to as Living Wyverns to distinguish them from their skeletal counterparts) are dragon-like monsters in the Asgarnian Ice Dungeon and the Ice Plateau. They were first revealed at RuneFest 2015 after being pitched on RuneLabs and being one of the November poll winners. They require level 96 Slayer to be killed. Wyverns reside in an icy cavern beneath the area in which Skeletal Wyverns reside. When killing Wyverns, an elite version may spawn (guaranteed while on a Slayer assignment), which can be further increased with the use of fellstalk incense sticks and tier 3 or higher luck.

Like their skeletal counterpart, Dragon Slayer bonuses do not work against living wyverns.

Getting there[edit | edit source]

  • For the Living Wyverns in the Asgarnian Ice Dungeon:
    1. Go to the Asgarnian Ice Dungeon resource dungeon, either using the Port Sarim lodestone, fairy ring code AIQ to Mudskipper Point, or teleport with the Hoardstalker ring or Dungeoneering cape (0,8).
    2. Head south to the skeletal wyverns' cave (marked on the in-game map)
    3. Go to the south-west corner and descend down the rope.
  • For the Ice Plateau in the Wilderness:
    1. Use the Wilderness Obelisks system to teleport to the obelisk on the Frozen plateau in level 44 Wilderness and then run Northwest. If the hard Wilderness achievements have been completed, the level 44 Wilderness obelisk can be directly selected. Otherwise it may take multiple attempts to arrive at the correct obelisk. The tradeable single-use item obelisk shard or its untradeable infinite charge version portable obelisk can be used to access the obelisks.

Strategies[edit | edit source]

Wyverns attack with all three combat styles and two breath attacks; the standard wyvern ice breath, and a poisonous ice breath. Whenever the wyvern uses the poisonous ice breath, a message will appear and say "A strong wyvern poison corrodes into your bones." Using elemental workshop shields of any sort, dragonfire shield or the wyrmfire potion will block the damage from their ice breath attacks, but will not protect against the ensuing poison attacks.

Wyverns also utilise the Cavern Chill debuff which starts at 20%; the player is experiencing the "Cold" mechanic and should light one of the static fires nearby. As the player's chill percent increases, an icy overlay becomes more visible on their screen. Several mechanics will take place depending on the percentage of chill:

  • Warm (0%): Wyvern poison damage increased up to 900 per five ticks.
  • Cold (25%): Wyvern attack damage greatly increases to around 2,500. The damage will continue to increase as the percentage of chill increases.
  • Colder (73%): The player no longer receives poison damage from Wyverns.
  • Coldest (100%): The player will be constantly stunned at 10.2 seconds per stun.

The lower the player's chill percent is, the higher the poison damage they will take, starting at 900 poison damage every five ticks at 0% chill. The poison damage will scale down linearly as the chill percent increases. At 73% chill, the poison damage completely stops. A downside to this is that the Wyverns' basic attacks will get stronger the higher the player's chill percent is, though moving into melee distance and using the appropriate prayer/curses will greatly reduce the damage the player takes.

Standing within a 5x5 of a lit fire will lower the chill percent by 3%–4% every three ticks. Lit fires last for 45 seconds before they must be lit again. The chill effects can be reset by leaving the cavern.

Antipoison++ will halve the damage of the poison, but each tick of poison damage will decrease the time left on the antipoison potion to the nearest 15-second interval. For example, if the player has 36 seconds left on their antipoison timer, the poison will remove six seconds. Overload salve's antipoison duration is affected by the poison breath but will protect from the Wyvern's ice breath. The poison caused by the Wyvern attacks ignore the effects of the poison purge auras, the venomblood perk, incense sticks and the anti-poison totem from Dungeoneering.

Wyverns attack in a manner similar to Araxxi; at a distance they use both magic and ranged attacks. If the player is next to them, they will primarily attack with melee. It is highly recommended to fight them in melee distance regardless of equipment used, because the Wyvern's melee attack is weaker and easier to predict, whereas the magic and ranged attacks are nearly impossible to predict and the attack immediately deals damage before the projectiles even hit the player.

Like the cave itself, the wyverns in the Wilderness also make use of the Cavern Chill mechanic. While players can enjoy the benefits of the Infernal Puzzle Box and the Stone of Jas buff while killing wyverns, the only drawback to this location is that they're much more packed compared to the cave, and it is not uncommon for another wyvern to attack while the player is fighting one. Therefore, if killing in the Wilderness, players should stay by the edges.

Update history[edit | edit source]

This information has been compiled as part of the update history project. Some updates may not be included – see here for how to help out!
  • ninja 13 March 2023 (Update):
    • Campfires are now present in the Wyvern area south of the Frozen Waste Plateau.
  • update 1 August 2022 (Update):
    • Removed the ice warriors, ice giants and ice spiders from the area, replacing them with glacors, Wyverns and acheron mammoths respectively.
  • patch 11 September 2017 (Update):
    • The following changes have been made to Living Wyverns:
      • The radius of the fires warming effect has been increased from 1 tile to 2.
      • The fire is now 4 times more effective.
      • The environment freezing effect now takes twice as long to build stacks.
      • The Wyverns' attack speed has been reduced.
  • ninja 28 November 2016 (Update):
    • Weapon drops from Wyverns, ripper demons, camel warriors and Acheron mammoths now have a greater chance of being dropped during a Slayer assignment.
  • ninja 14 December 2015 (Update):
    • Added quick chat options for declaring celestial dragon, Wyvern, ripper demon, camel warrior and Acheron mammoth kills.
  • patch 7 December 2015 (Update):
    • The Slayer XP of Living Wyverns was increased by between 50-200%.
  • patch 16 November 2015 (Update):
    • The drop rate of items on Living Wyverns has been buffed. The average drop should be worth approximately 15k.
  • patch 9 November 2015 (Update):
    • Preferring, blocking or quick-chatting a Wyvern Slayer assignment will now display correct feedback.
  • update 2 November 2015 (Update):
    • Added to game.

Trivia[edit | edit source]

  • Living wyverns where pitched on Runelabs by the player Anarchy Time.
  • Wyverns are referred to as living wyverns in the beast tab kill count interface.
  • There was a glitch where if assigned wyverns, when quickchatted it would say you are assigned "Nothing", including if they are preferred or blocked. This did not affect the built-in slayer counter however, and has since been fixed.
  • The drop table for wyverns was buffed on 16 November 2015.
  • Due to player complaints about how difficult wyverns were compared other slayer monsters of their level, they were given several changes with the 11 September 2017 update:
    • The lit fires were given an increased area of effect from a 3x3 to a 5x5 radius. Lit fires also removed frost stacks at a faster rate from 1% to 3%.
    • Their attack speed was lowered significantly.
    • The frost stacks take twice as long to accumulate.
  • As of 6 May 2018, the highest kill count for this monster was 28,252.[4]
